(117, 'Syrian troops advance near Aleppo, water cut off across city', '<p><a href="https://news.yahoo.com/un-says-2-million-people-aleppo-without-running-091302128.html"><img src="https://s.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/4VHf6syepRzncTXD79NRxA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3NfbGVnbztmaT1maWxsO2g9ODY7cT03NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/53db82f1438940b39ad0f518e78967ee.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="File - In this Friday, Sept. 23, 2016, file photo, in this photo provided by the Syrian Civil Defense group known as the White Helmets, a destroyed ambulance is seen outside the Syrian Civil Defense main center after airstrikes in Ansari neighborhood in the rebel-held part of eastern Aleppo, Syria. Violence in Aleppo has surged in recent days as a U.S.-Russia-brokered cease-fire collapsed after one week. The Syrian government and its ally Russia have resumed intense airstrikes and Syrian military officials have spoken of a looming ground offensive against rebel-held districts. (Syrian Civil Defense White Helmets via AP)" align="left" title="File - In this Friday, Sept. 23, 2016, file photo, in this photo provided by the Syrian Civil Defense group known as the White Helmets, a destroyed ambulance is seen outside the Syrian Civil Defense main center after airstrikes in Ansari neighborhood in the rebel-held part of eastern Aleppo, Syria. Violence in Aleppo has surged in recent days as a U.S.-Russia-brokered cease-fire collapsed after one week. The Syrian government and its ally Russia have resumed intense airstrikes and Syrian military officials have spoken of a looming ground offensive against rebel-held districts. (Syrian Civil Defense White Helmets via AP)" border="0" /></a>BEIRUT (AP) — Syrian government forces captured a rebel-held area on the edge of Aleppo on Saturday, tightening their siege on opposition-held neighborhoods in the northern city as an ongoing wave of airstrikes destroyed more buildings.</p><br clear="all"/>', '2016-09-24 13:00:55', '0', 0, 0, 'https://news.yahoo.com/un-says-2-million-people-aleppo-without-running-091302128.html', '', 3),
(118, 'Vijay, Pujara build commanding 1st test lead for India vs NZ', '<p><a href="https://news.yahoo.com/nz-238-5-reply-indias-318-064614964.html"><img src="https://s1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/JQ9vr8PqjgW3e6syF9Twzg--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3NfbGVnbztmaT1maWxsO2g9ODY7cT03NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/62fc015c126547268cc1caad620eac69.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="India&#039;s Cheteshwar Pujara, left, and Murali Vijay encourage each other during the third day of their first cricket test match against New Zealand in Kanpur, India, Saturday, Sept. 24, 2016. (AP Photo/Tsering Topgyal)" align="left" title="India&#039;s Cheteshwar Pujara, left, and Murali Vijay encourage each other during the third day of their first cricket test match against New Zealand in Kanpur, India, Saturday, Sept. 24, 2016. (AP Photo/Tsering Topgyal)" border="0" /></a>KANPUR, India (AP) — Murali Vijay and Cheteshwar Pujara put India in firm control of the first test on Saturday as the hosts reached 159-1 in their second innings at stumps on day three to lead New Zealand by 215 runs.</p><br clear="all"/>', '2016-09-24 12:47:19', '0', 0, 0, 'https://news.yahoo.com/nz-238-5-reply-indias-318-064614964.html', '', 3),
(119, 'Clinton leads Trump by 4 points ahead of first presidential debate: Reuters/Ipsos poll', '<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/clinton-leads-trump-4-points-ahead-first-us-193940421.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/SRaQQSCACvaVxBSLLInvKw--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3NfbGVnbztmaT1maWxsO2g9ODY7cT03NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2016-09-23T193940Z_1_LYNXNPEC8M1AC_RTROPTP_2_USA-ELECTION-CLINTON.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton arrives at a campaign event in Orlando" align="left" title="U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton arrives at a campaign event in Orlando" border="0" /></a>Democrat Hillary Clinton had a four-percentage point advantage in support over Republican Donald Trump ahead of their first U.S. presidential debate, according to the latest Reuters/Ipsos national tracking poll released on Friday. The Sept. 16-22 opinion poll showed that 41 percent of likely voters supported Clinton, while 37 percent supported Trump. Clinton has mostly led Trump in the poll during the 2016 campaign, though her advantage has narrowed since the end of the Democratic and Republican national conventions in July.</p><br clear="all"/>', '2016-09-23 19:49:16', '0', 0, 0, 'http://news.yahoo.com/clinton-leads-trump-4-points-ahead-first-us-193940421.html', '', 4),
(120, 'Obama vetoes Sept. 11 Saudi bill, sets up showdown with Congress', '<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/obama-faces-prospect-first-veto-override-sept-11-170115544.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/MSGFIRWlDiCHQC6J3HNewA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3NfbGVnbztmaT1maWxsO2g9ODY7cT03NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2016-09-23T170115Z_1_LYNXNPEC8M14Z_RTROPTP_2_USA-OBAMA.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="President Barack Obama walks to the the Oval Office of the White House" align="left" title="President Barack Obama walks to the the Oval Office of the White House" border="0" /></a>By Patricia Zengerle and Roberta Rampton WASHINGTON (Reuters) - President Barack Obama on Friday vetoed legislation allowing families of victims of the Sept. 11 attacks to sue Saudi Arabia, which could prompt Congress to overturn his decision with a rare veto override, the first of his presidency. Obama said the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act would hurt U.S. national security and harm important alliances, while shifting crucial terrorism-related issues from policy officials into the hands of the courts. The bill passed the Senate and House of Representatives in reaction to long-running suspicions, denied by Saudi Arabia, that hijackers of the four U.S. jetliners that attacked the United States in 2001 were backed by the Saudi government.</p><br clear="all"/>', '2016-09-23 22:44:29', '0', 0, 0, 'http://news.yahoo.com/obama-faces-prospect-first-veto-override-sept-11-170115544.html', '', 4),
(121, 'Hillary Clinton postpones trip to Charlotte -campaign statement', '<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/hillary-clinton-postpones-trip-charlotte-campaign-statement-015700659.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/wBFjWfPOCy7hgN6sSPfjBA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3NfbGVnbztmaT1maWxsO2g9ODY7cT03NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2016-09-24T015700Z_1_LYNXNPEC8N012_RTROPTP_2_USA-ELECTION-CLINTON.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton reads a piece of paper as she flies back to White Plains, after attending a campaign event in Orlando Florida, U.S." align="left" title="U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton reads a piece of paper as she flies back to White Plains, after attending a campaign event in Orlando Florida, U.S." border="0" /></a>U.S. Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton has postponed a trip planned for Sunday to Charlotte, North Carolina, which has seen sometimes violent protests after a black man was killed by police earlier this week. &quot;Hillary is grateful for, and intends to honor, the invitation from faith leaders to visit with the Charlotte community,&quot; her campaign said in a statement on Friday. &quot;After further discussion with community leaders, we have decided to postpone Sunday&#039;s trip as to not impact the city&#039;s resources,&quot; it said, adding that Clinton will visit the city on the following Sunday.</p><br clear="all"/>', '2016-09-24 01:57:00', '0', 0, 0, 'http://news.yahoo.com/hillary-clinton-postpones-trip-charlotte-campaign-statement-015700659.html', '', 4),
(122, 'Ohio system of purging inactive voters not legal: court', 'By Kim Palmer CLEVELAND (Reuters) - Ohio\'s practice of rescinding voter registrations from people who fail to cast ballots is illegal, a court ruled on Friday, the latest legal decision affecting voting rights ahead of the U.S. presidential election on Nov. 8. The decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit in Cincinnati reversed an earlier ruling by a federal judge in June and could lead to the reinstatement of thousands of voters in the politically crucial swing state of Ohio. "We don\'t believe that any voters should be removed from the rolls simply because they haven\'t voted in a few elections," said Mike Brickner, senior policy director at the American Civil Liberties Union, which brought a lawsuit against the practice along with other advocates.', '2016-09-24 05:33:12', '0', 0, 0, 'http://news.yahoo.com/ohio-system-purging-inactive-voters-not-legal-court-053312425.html', '', 4),
